<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="563" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,787,1318]" pageId="5" pageNumber="563">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,438,787,813]" pageId="5" pageNumber="563">Short description. Male.</emphasis>
<emphasis box="[444,534,787,813]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="563">Clypeus</emphasis>
: basal process broad and apically bilobed; outer lobe rounded and smooth or with a small acute projection on inner side which is not seen in some cases; inner lobe more conical and sharp-pointed; lamelliform process small and rounded; apical joint strongly curved inwards, apically blunt and broad (
<figureCitation box="[1271,1366,859,885]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1839,1863]" captionTargetBox="[166,1422,181,1803]" captionTargetId="figure-17@6.[154,1434,181,1813]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 3. Male of Branchipodopsis affinis. A1, dorsal view of clypeus, arrow indicates small projection on apex of outer lobe of basal process. A2, variability of the basal antennal processes in adults. B, cercopods, arrow indicates spines on ventral surface of last abdominal segment. C, ventral view of gonopods, arrow indicates peg-like projection distally on lateral margin. Scale bars: 200μm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4447304" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4447304/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="563">Fig. 3 A</figureCitation>
<figureCitation box="[1366,1376,859,885]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1473,1497]" captionTargetBox="[156,1430,342,1447]" captionTargetId="figure-95@2.[156,1430,342,1447]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Study area map showing the location of temporary pools." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4447300" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4447300/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="563">1</figureCitation>
, A 
<figureCitation box="[1409,1424,859,885]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,913,937]" captionTargetBox="[160,1430,185,884]" captionTargetId="figure-17@4.[156,1432,181,889]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Proportional abundance (%) of the main zooplankton groups in temporary pools. The size of pools increases from left to right. For the codes see table 1." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4447302" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4447302/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="563">2</figureCitation>
). 
<emphasis box="[151,271,895,921]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="563">Cercopods</emphasis>
: outer margins strongly convex with setae along entire length; small spine like setae on inner margins along entire length (
<figureCitation box="[378,466,931,957]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1839,1863]" captionTargetBox="[166,1422,181,1803]" captionTargetId="figure-17@6.[154,1434,181,1813]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 3. Male of Branchipodopsis affinis. A1, dorsal view of clypeus, arrow indicates small projection on apex of outer lobe of basal process. A2, variability of the basal antennal processes in adults. B, cercopods, arrow indicates spines on ventral surface of last abdominal segment. C, ventral view of gonopods, arrow indicates peg-like projection distally on lateral margin. Scale bars: 200μm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4447304" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4447304/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="563">Fig. 3B</figureCitation>
). 
<emphasis box="[487,688,931,957]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="563">Abdominal spines</emphasis>
: pair of small spines on ventral surface of last abdominal segment (
<figureCitation box="[160,249,967,993]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1839,1863]" captionTargetBox="[166,1422,181,1803]" captionTargetId="figure-17@6.[154,1434,181,1813]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 3. Male of Branchipodopsis affinis. A1, dorsal view of clypeus, arrow indicates small projection on apex of outer lobe of basal process. A2, variability of the basal antennal processes in adults. B, cercopods, arrow indicates spines on ventral surface of last abdominal segment. C, ventral view of gonopods, arrow indicates peg-like projection distally on lateral margin. Scale bars: 200μm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4447304" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4447304/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="563">Fig. 3C</figureCitation>
). 
<emphasis box="[271,386,967,993]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="563">Gonopods</emphasis>
: basal part with large rounded projection on median margin and small, but distinct, peg-like projection distally on lateral margin (
<figureCitation box="[574,664,1003,1029]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1839,1863]" captionTargetBox="[166,1422,181,1803]" captionTargetId="figure-17@6.[154,1434,181,1813]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 3. Male of Branchipodopsis affinis. A1, dorsal view of clypeus, arrow indicates small projection on apex of outer lobe of basal process. A2, variability of the basal antennal processes in adults. B, cercopods, arrow indicates spines on ventral surface of last abdominal segment. C, ventral view of gonopods, arrow indicates peg-like projection distally on lateral margin. Scale bars: 200μm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4447304" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4447304/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="563">Fig. 3C</figureCitation>
). 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[686,780,1003,1029]" pageId="5" pageNumber="563">Female.</emphasis>
<emphasis box="[788,881,1003,1029]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="563">Antenna</emphasis>
: proximal four fifths cylindrical; distal fifth narrowing to tapering point (
<figureCitation box="[435,530,1039,1065]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1778,1802]" captionTargetBox="[154,1423,189,1750]" captionTargetId="figure-33@7.[154,1433,181,1753]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 4. Female of Branchipodopsis affinis. A, dorsal view of head. B, lateral view of genital segments. C, cercopods. Scale bars: 200μm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4447306" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4447306/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="563">Fig. 4 A</figureCitation>
). 
<emphasis box="[549,742,1039,1065]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="563">Genital segments</emphasis>
inconspicuously swollen and brood pouch oval shaped (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1778,1802]" captionTargetBox="[154,1423,189,1750]" captionTargetId="figure-33@7.[154,1433,181,1753]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 4. Female of Branchipodopsis affinis. A, dorsal view of head. B, lateral view of genital segments. C, cercopods. Scale bars: 200μm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4447306" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4447306/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="563">Fig. 4 B</figureCitation>
). 
<emphasis box="[192,312,1075,1101]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="563">Cercopods</emphasis>
: margins straight with long plumose setae along outer margins and distal two thirds of inner margins; proximal thirds inner margins with short plumose setae (
<figureCitation box="[784,873,1111,1137]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1778,1802]" captionTargetBox="[154,1423,189,1750]" captionTargetId="figure-33@7.[154,1433,181,1753]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 4. Female of Branchipodopsis affinis. A, dorsal view of head. B, lateral view of genital segments. C, cercopods. Scale bars: 200μm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4447306" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4447306/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="563">Fig. 4C</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,787,1318]" box="[199,587,1147,1174]" pageId="5" pageNumber="563">Evolutionary relationships of taxa.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="563" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,787,1318]" pageId="5" pageNumber="563">
The results indicated that the Neighbor-Joining method divided 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Sars" authorityYear="1901" box="[909,1175,1183,1209]" class="Branchiopoda" family="Branchipodidae" genus="Branchipodopsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anostraca" pageId="5" pageNumber="563" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="affinis">
<emphasis box="[909,1175,1183,1209]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="563">Branchipodopsis affinis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and all other species of the genus to two main clades, although with lower bootstrap values (
<figureCitation box="[910,977,1219,1246]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="8.[151,250,812,836]" captionTargetBox="[168,1419,183,788]" captionTargetId="figure-17@8.[161,1426,181,788]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 5. Neighbor-Joining tree based on the mitochondrial data set of Branchipodopsis species. Artemia urmiana. is used as outgroup. The numbers at the nodes indicate levels of bootstrap support (%)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4447308" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4447308/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="563">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
). Based on these results the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Sars" authorityYear="1901" box="[1290,1390,1219,1245]" class="Branchiopoda" family="Branchipodidae" genus="Branchipodopsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anostraca" pageId="5" pageNumber="563" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="affinis">
<emphasis box="[1290,1390,1219,1245]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="563">B. affinis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[151,344,1255,1281]" class="Branchiopoda" family="Artemiidae" genus="Artemia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anostraca" pageId="5" pageNumber="563" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="urmiana">
<emphasis box="[151,344,1255,1281]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="563">Artemia urmiana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
groups are comprised of two sub-clades, in which the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Sars" authorityYear="1901" box="[959,1061,1255,1281]" class="Branchiopoda" family="Branchipodidae" genus="Branchipodopsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anostraca" pageId="5" pageNumber="563" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="affinis">
<emphasis box="[959,1061,1255,1281]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="563">B. affinis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
represents % 80 separation clade from the 
<taxonomicName box="[254,446,1291,1317]" class="Branchiopoda" family="Artemiidae" genus="Artemia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anostraca" pageId="5" pageNumber="563" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="urmiana">
<emphasis box="[254,446,1291,1317]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="563">Artemia urmiana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
groups.
</paragraph>
